  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset, deposited on Dryad and associated with the study \"Home alone: Remote work, isolation, and mental health\" by Natalia Emanuel, Amanda Pallais, and Emma Harrington, is a recently released resource that has recorded four downloads since publication. While online engagement remains in its earliest stages, the dataset has been formally cited by a paper published in <em>Science</em>, signaling meaningful scholarly recognition from a high-profile outlet.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset was produced by a cross-institutional team spanning the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, Harvard University, and the University of Virginia \u2014 a collaboration that brings together economic and psychological perspectives on the consequences of remote work. Its thematic focus centers on mental health, social isolation, and psychological distress in the context of shifting work arrangements, topics that gained particular urgency during and after the COVID-19 pandemic. The conceptual landscape of the dataset, as indexed, encompasses mental distress, social isolation, and pandemic-era work patterns, situating it at the intersection of labor economics and public health research.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset's most notable signal of impact is its citation by a study published in <em>Science</em> (DOI recorded via DataCite), one of the world's most selective and widely read scientific journals. Being cited at this level so shortly after deposit is a strong early indicator of scholarly relevance, suggesting that the underlying data is already being integrated into high-stakes academic discourse on remote work and worker wellbeing. This citation alone distinguishes the dataset from the vast majority of newly deposited research data, which often languishes unnoticed in the period immediately following release.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of direct usage, the dataset has accumulated four downloads through Dryad, the open-access repository that hosts it. Dryad is a well-established, DOI-issuing platform serving both life sciences and social sciences, and its open access policy ensures the data is available to any researcher without restriction or embargo. While four downloads is a modest figure in absolute terms, the dataset's 2026 release date means it has had limited time to accumulate usage, and early download activity combined with a high-profile citation paints a picture of a resource that is beginning to find its audience.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Broader dissemination signals \u2014 such as social media discussion, policy mentions, or teaching adoption \u2014 are not yet measurable for this dataset, which is consistent with its very recent publication. The attention infrastructure data does indicate that the associated research exists within a topic area tracked across a substantial number of Substack channels and other online sources, reflecting sustained public and professional interest in remote work and mental health as subject areas. As the companion scholarly article circulates more widely, it is reasonable to expect that data reuse and citation activity will grow accordingly.</p>",
